               <note>
                  
                  <ab type="history">The kingdom of Dāmot seems to have been in existence at least as early as the 10th century in the region immediately south of the 
                     <placeName ref="LOC1022Abbay"/> in the present-day <placeName ref="LOC6178Wallag"/> and Western <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa"/>. 
                     Its bounds are uncertain, but they may have stretched as far west as  <placeName ref="LOC2667Didess"/>
                     river as far south as <placeName ref="LOC6165Walamo"/>. It is believed that  Dāmot  from the 10th to the 13th century was the dominant power over both the Christian and Muslim principalities. 
                     However, in the late 13th century <persName ref="PRS10303Yekunno"/> drove Dāmot from the <placeName ref="LOC5597Sawa"/>n plateau, 
                     but it was <roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</roleName><persName ref="PRS1854Amdase"/> in the early 14th century who subjugating the kingdom.
                     There after the Christian culture slowly diffused among the population. By the 16th century, Dāmot had become an integral province of the Christian kingdom of
                     <placeName ref="LOC3010Ethiop"/>. During the mid sixteenth century, the partly christianized population joined with their <persName ref="ETH1126Amhara"/> and 
                     <persName ref="ETH2125Tegre"/> in fighting against the Muslim invasion of <persName ref="PRS1522Ahmadb"/>. In the late sixteenth century, Dāmot  was occupied by the 
                     <persName ref="ETH1973Oromo"/>who made their new homeland. Throughout the 17th and 18th century Dāmot allied itself with 
                     <placeName ref="LOC3549Gojjam"/>and<placeName ref="LOC5284Qwara"/> in pursuit of influence and power in <placeName ref="LOC3577Gondar"/>.
                     In the mid 20th century, Dāmot was incorporated into the province of  <placeName ref="LOC3549Gojjam"/>as an ʾawrāǧǧā.
                        
                  </ab>
